---
import SchemaLayout from '../../../layouts/SchemaLayout.astro';
import drugsData from '../../../../data/drugs.json';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;

// Highly protein-bound drugs from the database
const highProteinBinding = (drugsData as any[]).filter(d => {
  const pb = d.pharmacokinetics?.protein_binding || '';
  const pbLower = pb.toLowerCase();
  // Check for percentage ≥ 85%
  const match = pb.match(/(\d+)/g);
  if (match) {
    const nums = match.map(Number);
    const maxVal = Math.max(...nums);
    if (maxVal >= 85) return true;
  }
  // Check for qualitative descriptors
  return pbLower.includes('high') || pbLower.includes('extensive') || pbLower.includes('>90') ||
    pbLower.includes('>85') || pbLower.includes('>95') || pbLower.includes('>99');
});

// Drugs with protein binding displacement interaction tags
const displacementDrugs = (drugsData as any[]).filter(d =>
  (d.interaction_tags || []).some((t: string) => t.toLowerCase().includes('protein-binding') || t.toLowerCase().includes('bilirubin-displacement'))
);

// Key highly protein-bound drugs (curated)
const curatedHighPB = [
  { drug: 'Warfarin', binding: '99%', protein: 'Albumin (primarily)', clinical: 'Displacement interactions historically cited but clinical magnitude debated; NSAIDs, phenytoin, sulfonamides cited as displacers; transient increase in free fraction rapidly corrected by increased clearance.' },
  { drug: 'Phenytoin', binding: '90%', protein: 'Albumin', clinical: 'Decreased binding in hypoalbuminemia, uremia, and pregnancy elevates free fraction. Measure free phenytoin levels in these populations; total level interpretation is unreliable.' },
  { drug: 'Valproate', binding: '85–95%', protein: 'Albumin (saturable)', clinical: 'Protein binding becomes saturated at high doses, causing disproportionate increases in free fraction; free valproate monitoring may be needed in toxicity evaluation.' },
  { drug: 'NSAIDs (ibuprofen, naproxen)', binding: '>99%', protein: 'Albumin', clinical: 'NSAIDs can displace other highly albumin-bound drugs; most clinically significant displacement effect is on warfarin — though PK studies show the total warfarin level falls rapidly, making it a transient interaction.' },
  { drug: 'Diazepam', binding: '98%', protein: 'Albumin', clinical: 'Free fraction increases in hypoalbuminemia and with displacing drugs; CNS effects may be more pronounced in critically ill patients with low albumin.' },
  { drug: 'Cyclosporine', binding: '90%', protein: 'Lipoproteins and erythrocytes (not primarily albumin)', clinical: 'Binding to lipoproteins means that hyperlipidemia changes can affect drug distribution; whole blood level (not plasma level) is used for monitoring.' },
  { drug: 'Amiodarone', binding: '>96%', protein: 'Albumin', clinical: 'Highly lipophilic; massive Vd (~60 L/kg). Protein binding displacement contributes marginally to its interactions relative to its profound CYP and P-gp inhibitory effects.' },
  { drug: 'Furosemide', binding: '91–99%', protein: 'Albumin', clinical: 'In severe hypoalbuminemia, reduced protein binding reduces tubular delivery of furosemide to its site of action — a pharmacokinetic basis for loop diuretic resistance in nephrotic syndrome.' },
  { drug: 'Ceftriaxone', binding: '85–95%', protein: 'Albumin', clinical: 'In neonates, ceftriaxone displaces bilirubin from albumin binding sites, raising free bilirubin and risking kernicterus — absolute contraindication in neonates receiving calcium or hyperbilirubinemic neonates.' },
];
---
<SchemaLayout
  title="Protein Binding Displacement — Drug Interactions"
  schema="drug-interactions"
  description="Plasma protein binding, albumin displacement interactions, clinical magnitude of effect, and the common misconception about the significance of displacement in practice."
>
  <div class="mb-6">
    <div class="breadcrumbs text-sm mb-4">
      <ul>
        <li><a href={`${base}schemas/09-drug-interactions/`} class="link link-hover">Drug Interactions</a></li>
        <li>Protein Binding</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-serif font-bold mb-2">Protein Binding &amp; Displacement Interactions</h1>
    <p class="text-base-content/70 text-lg">Plasma albumin binding, free drug fraction, and the clinical reality of displacement interactions</p>
  </div>

  <div class="prose max-w-none mb-10">
    <p>
      The concept that drugs must be pharmacologically "free" — unbound to plasma proteins —
      to exert their effects is a foundational principle of clinical pharmacokinetics.
      Of the plasma proteins that bind drugs, albumin is quantitatively dominant, binding
      the vast majority of acidic drugs (including warfarin, NSAIDs, phenytoin, valproate,
      furosemide, and most penicillins) via two primary binding sites. Basic drugs (opioids,
      propranolol, lidocaine, amitriptyline, quinidine) bind preferentially to α1-acid
      glycoprotein (AAG), an acute-phase reactant whose concentration rises during stress,
      infection, and post-surgery, temporarily increasing binding of basic drugs in
      those states. Lipoproteins bind lipophilic drugs including cyclosporine and
      amiodarone. The free (unbound) fraction determines the pharmacodynamic effect
      because only free drug crosses membranes, reaches receptors, and is subject to
      hepatic extraction and renal filtration for elimination.
    </p>
    <p>
      Protein binding displacement occurs when drug A displaces drug B from albumin
      binding sites, transiently increasing the free fraction of drug B. For decades,
      this was taught as a clinically significant interaction mechanism — warfarin displaced
      by NSAIDs, phenytoin displaced by valproate — with the implication that displacement
      raises free drug concentrations and pharmacodynamic effect. Modern pharmacokinetic
      analysis has substantially revised this teaching. The critical insight is that an
      increase in the free fraction of drug B also increases its clearance: the liver and
      kidney, which can only eliminate free drug, now have more substrate available and
      accelerate elimination proportionally. For drugs with low hepatic extraction ratios
      — the majority of clinically relevant highly protein-bound drugs, including warfarin
      and phenytoin — clearance is directly proportional to the free fraction (capacity-limited
      or restrictive clearance model). Within hours to days, a new steady state is established
      where the free concentration returns to its original value despite a lower total
      drug concentration. The "interaction" produces a transient and self-correcting
      change in total drug level, not a sustained elevation in free drug effect. This
      is why isolated protein-binding displacement in vitro does not reliably predict
      clinically significant pharmacodynamic change in vivo.
    </p>
    <p>
      Despite this revision, several clinically important exceptions justify continued
      attention to protein-binding displacement. First, for drugs with high hepatic
      extraction ratios (high-extraction or flow-limited clearance, where elimination
      depends on hepatic blood flow rather than free fraction — lidocaine, propranolol,
      morphine), displacement does not accelerate clearance proportionally and free
      concentration can transiently rise with clinical effect. Second, displacement is
      clinically significant when the volume of distribution is small (highly protein-bound
      drug confined to plasma, little tissue distribution) and the therapeutic margin is
      narrow — conditions partially met by warfarin and phenytoin. Third, the context of
      co-occurring pharmacokinetic interactions (where the displacer also inhibits CYP
      or renal elimination of the displaced drug) converts a pharmacokinetically
      insignificant displacement into a clinically dangerous combination, because
      increased free fraction cannot be rapidly cleared. The warfarin-phenylbutazone
      combination (now largely historical) caused fatal bleeding through exactly this
      mechanism: phenylbutazone displaced warfarin from albumin while simultaneously
      inhibiting its CYP2C9-mediated elimination, producing a sustained elevation in
      free warfarin concentration. When interpreting reports of protein-binding displacement
      interactions, the student should ask: is there also a PK elimination interaction
      that would prevent compensatory clearance?
    </p>
    <p>
      Hypoalbuminemia is the clinically encountered condition that most reliably elevates
      free drug fractions of albumin-bound drugs with physiological rather than
      drug-induced displacement as the cause. Albumin levels below 2.0 g/dL —
      common in severe liver disease, nephrotic syndrome, malnutrition, and critical
      illness — can double the free fraction of phenytoin, warfarin, and valproate.
      For phenytoin, the total plasma concentration is a misleading guide in
      hypoalbuminemic patients: total phenytoin levels may appear therapeutic or
      sub-therapeutic while free levels are supratherapeutic and toxic. The Sheiner-Tozer
      equation (adjusted phenytoin = measured total / [0.2 × albumin + 0.1]) corrects
      for hypoalbuminemia, but direct measurement of free phenytoin is preferred in
      complex patients. Similarly, uremia alters phenytoin protein binding through
      competitive displacement of uremic retention solutes from albumin, an important
      consideration in patients with end-stage renal disease on phenytoin. Nurses
      caring for patients with liver disease, nephrotic syndrome, or critical illness
      should be aware that "normal" total drug levels may represent overexposure
      when protein binding is reduced, and should communicate this to the prescriber
      when toxicity signs appear at seemingly therapeutic drug levels.
    </p>
  </div>

  <!-- Highly Protein-Bound Drugs — Curated -->
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-serif font-bold mb-4">High Clinical-Priority Highly Protein-Bound Drugs</h2>
  <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-10">
    <table class="table table-zebra w-full">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Drug</th>
          <th>Protein Binding</th>
          <th>Binding Protein</th>
          <th>Clinical Note</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {curatedHighPB.map(entry => (
          <tr>
            <td class="font-medium">{entry.drug}</td>
            <td><span class="badge badge-outline badge-sm font-mono">{entry.binding}</span></td>
            <td class="text-sm">{entry.protein}</td>
            <td class="text-sm max-w-sm">{entry.clinical}</td>
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- Highly protein-bound drugs from database -->
  {highProteinBinding.length > 0 && (
    <>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-serif font-bold mb-3">Highly Protein-Bound Drugs in the Database (≥85%)</h2>
      <p class="text-sm text-base-content/70 mb-4">
        These drugs may exhibit altered free fraction in hypoalbuminemia, uremia, or when displaced by competing drugs.
        Monitor free levels (not total) for narrow therapeutic index drugs (phenytoin, valproate) when albumin is low.
      </p>
      <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-10">
        <table class="table table-zebra table-sm w-full">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Drug</th>
              <th>Drug Class</th>
              <th>Protein Binding</th>
              <th>NTI</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            {highProteinBinding.map((drug: any) => {
              const ntiIds = new Set(['warfarin','phenytoin','digoxin','lithium','cyclosporine','tacrolimus',
                'methotrexate','vancomycin','valproate','carbamazepine','theophylline','amiodarone']);
              const isNTI = ntiIds.has(drug.id);
              return (
                <tr class={isNTI ? 'bg-error/5' : ''}>
                  <td>
                    <a href={`${base}drugs/${drug.id}/`} class="link link-hover font-medium">{drug.generic_name}</a>
                  </td>
                  <td class="text-sm">{drug.drug_class}</td>
                  <td class="font-mono text-sm">{drug.pharmacokinetics?.protein_binding || '—'}</td>
                  <td>
                    {isNTI && <span class="badge badge-error badge-xs">NTI</span>}
                  </td>
                </tr>
              );
            })}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </>
  )}

  <!-- Displacement-tagged drugs -->
  {displacementDrugs.length > 0 && (
    <>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-serif font-bold mb-3">Displacement-Related Interaction Tags in the Database</h2>
      <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-10">
        <table class="table table-zebra table-sm w-full">
          <thead><tr><th>Drug</th><th>Drug Class</th><th>Interaction Tags</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            {displacementDrugs.map((drug: any) => {
              const dispTags = (drug.interaction_tags||[]).filter((t:string) =>
                t.toLowerCase().includes('protein-binding') || t.toLowerCase().includes('bilirubin')
              );
              return (
                <tr>
                  <td><a href={`${base}drugs/${drug.id}/`} class="link link-hover">{drug.generic_name}</a></td>
                  <td class="text-sm">{drug.drug_class}</td>
                  <td>
                    {dispTags.map((t: string) => (
                      <span class="badge badge-outline badge-xs mr-1">{t}</span>
                    ))}
                  </td>
                </tr>
              );
            })}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </>
  )}

  <!-- Correcting the Misconception -->
  <div class="card bg-base-200 mb-10">
    <div class="card-body">
      <h3 class="card-title text-lg">⚠️ Correcting a Common Misconception</h3>
      <p class="text-sm">
        <strong>Myth:</strong> "Drug A displaces Drug B from protein → Drug B free fraction ↑ → Drug B toxicity."
      </p>
      <p class="text-sm mt-2">
        <strong>Reality:</strong> For most highly protein-bound drugs with low hepatic extraction ratios,
        displacement transiently raises free fraction → free drug is rapidly cleared (restrictive clearance model)
        → free concentration returns to baseline within hours; total concentration falls but free drug is unchanged at steady state.
        The "interaction" is pharmacokinetically self-correcting in most cases.
      </p>
      <p class="text-sm mt-2">
        <strong>Exceptions where displacement IS clinically significant:</strong>
      </p>
      <ul class="text-sm list-disc list-inside space-y-1 mt-1">
        <li>Concurrent CYP or elimination inhibition (displacement + impaired clearance = sustained free level elevation)</li>
        <li>Hypoalbuminemia (physiological, not drug-induced displacement — no compensatory albumin available)</li>
        <li>Uremia (endogenous displacing solutes + altered renal clearance)</li>
        <li>Neonatal hyperbilirubinemia: ceftriaxone displaces bilirubin → free bilirubin elevation → kernicterus risk</li>
        <li>High extraction ratio drugs: lidocaine, propranolol — clearance is flow-limited, not free fraction-limited</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="alert alert-info">
    <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" class="stroke-current shrink-0 w-6 h-6">
      <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M13 16h-1v-4h-1m1-4h.01M21 12a9 9 0 11-18 0 9 9 0 0118 0z"></path>
    </svg>
    <div>
      <p class="font-semibold">Clinical Monitoring Principle</p>
      <p class="text-sm">
        For narrow therapeutic index drugs (phenytoin, valproate, cyclosporine) in patients with albumin &lt;2.5 g/dL,
        uremia (CrCl &lt;20 mL/min), or critical illness: measure <strong>free drug concentrations</strong> rather than
        relying on total levels. Report unexplained toxicity at "therapeutic" total levels to the prescriber; free fraction
        measurement is indicated.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</SchemaLayout>
